what is labels and selector?

Labels (applied to any K8s object)
Labels are key-value pairs attached to objects (pods, nodes, services, deployments, etc.) to identify and organize them.

An object can have multiple labels
Labels can be added/updated anytime

metadata:
  labels:
    app: frontend
    env: production
    tier: web


Selectors (used to query/filter objects)
Selectors let you find and group objects based on their labels.


1. Equality-based

selector:
  app: frontend        # app == frontend
  env: production      # AND env == production


Real-World Example

apiVersion: apps/v1
kind: Deployment
metadata:
  name: frontend
spec:                              # 👈 SPEC 1 — Deployment's spec
  replicas: 2
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: frontend             # manages pods with this label
  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: frontend             # pods get this label
    spec:                                                         # 👈 SPEC 2 — Pod's spec
      containers:              # ← list of containers
      - name: frontend-app    # ← CONTAINER NAME
        image: nginx:1.21     # ← IMAGE (name:tag)
        ports:
        - containerPort: 80


Why Two Specs?

Because there are two different objects here:

Object        Its spec describes
Spec 1        Deployment   replicas, selector, template
Spec 2        Pod          containers, volumes, restartPolicy


What Each Part Does

label and selector in deployment itself

spec:
  selector:
    matchLabels:
      app: frontend   # 👈 Deployment LOOKS FOR pods with this label
                      #    (how it tracks & manages its pods)

  template:
    metadata:
      labels:
        app: frontend # 👈 Pods are CREATED WITH this label
                      #    (so the deployment can find them)


What Happens If They Don't Match?

selector:
  matchLabels:
    app: frontend    # looking for "frontend"

template:
  metadata:
    labels:
      app: backend   # but pods are created as "backend"

❌ Kubernetes will reject this with a validation error — they must match.
